<subSubSection id="2F80BF32248C2C59284C2537C69C3C1C" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="6383D4AC41CF058844467F83F2721663" pageNumber="1">Introduction</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AC8630BB2423E6030F94BB3D2368424B" pageNumber="1">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="006ED5D45B5BEEA3ECDD3ECB061DAE0C" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10DF0F9D-4060-4E5F-A156-DFE88550256D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Chromaphyosemion Aphyosemion Radda 1971:118" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Chromaphyosemion Radda, 1971</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="DEB83A4400544C64F6855CD3D1563C46" class="Actinopterygii" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Cyprinodontiformes</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName id="6E1C0196308B7D7830C54AF0AEC3BC3C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Nothobranchiidae</taxonomicName>
) is distributed in the coastal plains from southern Togo to northern Gabon. Its center of diversity lies within Cameroon, a pattern similar to that observed in other groups of nothobranchiids (
<taxonomicName id="1B8948FA6FD52CC8D08BE3492D59A12F" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:ECEABF8E-2CC0-400B-8150-E4FB816BA688" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Epiplatys" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Epiplatys sexfasciatus Gill 1862:136" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sexfasciatus">Epiplatys sexfasciatus</taxonomicName>
group, 
<taxonomicName id="B12C82FAF0E786A91CD3583CD87888F2" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:3C522D31-A885-4818-9B5C-ECD6A4F358D7" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Aphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Aphyosemion calliurum ahli Myers 1933:183" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="calliurum">Aphyosemion calliurum</taxonomicName>
group), lampeyes of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="365BDBD42A92910EC64713F077B1E8A0" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D8D993F2-FB1B-4C74-BC2C-F38D5A073B67" authority="Boulenger, 1904" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1904" class="Actinopterygii" family="Poeciliidae" genus="Procatopus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Procatopus Boulenger 1904:20" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Procatopus Boulenger, 1904</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="BCA7D9E79691F15E96D85CC0C053DEA7" class="Actinopterygii" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" phylum="Chordata" rank="order">Cyprinodontiformes</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="C29D4073BD7836E7357B9742F200B6F4" class="Actinopterygii" family="Poeciliidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Poeciliidae</taxonomicName>
), and in cichlids of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="F390E558FF9793850E09659A0B3152E2" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:1A6BE0F6-1AEF-40AB-AFEC-2143FAF7865C" authority="Lamboj, 2001" authorityName="Lamboj" authorityYear="2001" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Benitochromis" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Benitochromis Lamboj 2001:17" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Benitochromis Lamboj, 2001</taxonomicName>
. Most of the species of these groups are endemic to Cameroon, which also has the richest cyprinodontiform fauna in Africa with a high proportion of endemics (species numbers and distribution data from Huber 2000 and for the cichlids Lamboj 2004).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A8F69F8A4D6400C5E857E1ABA0690FB" lastPageNumber="2" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="5D4E04D23B06E32817C784823DE05D04" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10DF0F9D-4060-4E5F-A156-DFE88550256D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Chromaphyosemion Aphyosemion Radda 1971:118" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">Chromaphyosemion</taxonomicName>
is diagnosed as a monophylum by characteristic features which are unique in nothobranchiids including color patterns with two parallel black stripes on the sides, a unique black ventral head pattern and several rows of scales on sides (especially dorsally) with a metallic bluish, greenish, copper or golden coloration (Radda 1971; Sonnenberg 2000). Besides, species of the genus possess the ability of fast color changes, which for example is also known in cichlids (Fryer &amp; Iles 1972). This feature is unique within Nothobranchiinae, and is especially pronounced in adult males. It means that specimens can change from pale sides with clearly visible parallel black stripes within seconds into extremely colorful specimens (Figs. 1-2) and back. To some extent this can also include fin coloration and also is seen in females.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="82F607E583C0117858650B4900A6540E" lastPageNumber="3" pageNumber="2">
Species diagnoses in 
<taxonomicName id="37F1A5842EE017B60FF47B3108DD0546" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10DF0F9D-4060-4E5F-A156-DFE88550256D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Chromaphyosemion Aphyosemion Radda 1971:118" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">Chromaphyosemion</taxonomicName>
are often based, as in most aplocheiloid species groups, on male color patterns. The morphometric and meristic characters typically used in taxonomic research of nothobranchiids show often considerable overlap and are rarely diagnostic (Amiet 1987; Scheel 1966, 1968).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="761491F77D32B22FE82248E811E94300" pageNumber="3">
Amiet (1987) assumes that male coloration might be important in mate choice of females in nothobranchiid fishes. For this reason it may be particularly useful for taxonomic purposes because the species diagnosis would be based on the same characters which females use to distinguish between con- and heterospecific males. This is similar to the Specific Mate Recognition System (SMRS) as described by Paterson (1978). The potential applicability is basically supported by mate-choice experiments in several groups of cyprinodontiform fishes (e.g., Houde 1997; Kodric-Brown &amp; Strecker 2001; Strecker 2006; Strecker &amp; Kodric-Brown 1999, 2000; Brosset &amp; Lachaise 1995) and a first study in 
<taxonomicName id="A1D7924D357ED0AED1510A526D191AC3" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10DF0F9D-4060-4E5F-A156-DFE88550256D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Chromaphyosemion Aphyosemion Radda 1971:118" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">Chromaphyosemion</taxonomicName>
(Klemme 2005). This allows the assumption that the use of color patterns as diagnostic characters in species definitions has a real biological background and is not an artificial classification based on random variability. In addition, pheromones are also assumed to play a role in mate and species recognition in 
<taxonomicName id="79A0AD6F28E36BDE3FD1C0938890193B" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10DF0F9D-4060-4E5F-A156-DFE88550256D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Chromaphyosemion Aphyosemion Radda 1971:118" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">Chromaphyosemion</taxonomicName>
(Bathie 1972; Ewing &amp; Evans 1973).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B42BF455C380B11866AFEBC238FCBF2F" pageNumber="3">
The first review of 
<taxonomicName id="3AF91680667F09AFFD123D5D231F4C59" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10DF0F9D-4060-4E5F-A156-DFE88550256D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Chromaphyosemion Aphyosemion Radda 1971:118" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">Chromaphyosemion</taxonomicName>
was conducted by Scheel (1966, 1968, 1974, 1990), who studied morphology and karyotypes and carried out some crossing experiments. He disclosed, besides a conservative morphology, a confusing variety of karyotypes and crossing results (Scheel 1974). Recent studies (
<normalizedToken id="2DE037998865C2A95B30FE60E2394542" originalValue="Völker">Voelker</normalizedToken>
et al. 2005, 2006, 2007a, in press and pers. comm.) have confirmed that karyotype variation between and within species and even within populations is not unusual. Therefore karyotype differences alone are not a sufficient indicator of species differences or boundaries, especially as their impact on reproductive isolation and speciation is not well known (e.g., Rieseberg 2001).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1CA2BB54D8C059F0FBD57E21C8345908" pageNumber="3">
Crossing experiments, usually performed in a no-choice experimental setup (Scheel 1966, 1968, 1974; Huber 1998a, 2000), showed different degrees of hybrid infertility. A histological study of the reproductive tissues of several crosses of 
<taxonomicName id="23A7FC76E425B5F3AF7D1ED454B08C1F" authority="Ahl, 1924" authorityName="Ahl" authorityYear="1924" baseAuthorityName="Ahl" baseAuthorityYear="1924" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bitaeniatum">C. bitaeniatum (Ahl, 1924)</taxonomicName>
populations by 
<normalizedToken id="D8BC241CF585CCBF0E09D4C8BFE2CCFC" originalValue="Schröder">Schroeder</normalizedToken>
(1967) indicated that, even within a diagnosable species, incompatibilities including hybrid sterility exist. Similar results were found by Scheel (1974) for 
<taxonomicName id="34F0963031CF7F89F3FE2D58364157C0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="riggenbachi">C. riggenbachi</taxonomicName>
. These results imply that crossing experiments alone are insufficient to establish taxonomic relationships (for further discussion see Kottelat 1997).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E880A8142AF0AFB1185F3290A20D8DD1" pageNumber="3">
Scheel (1974) used the oldest available name, 
<taxonomicName id="C5DB9680671ED2300818C0851FA82662" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:78C80644-7E92-46C8-8753-3D4BA9CB628B" authority="Loennberg, 1895" authorityName="Loennberg" authorityYear="1895" baseAuthorityName="Loennberg" baseAuthorityYear="1895" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Aphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Aphyosemion bivittatum hollyi Myers 1933:184" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bivittatum">
Aphyosemion bivittatum (
<normalizedToken id="30B8EF93997C868213FF215E79C2DCFA" originalValue="Lönnberg">Loennberg</normalizedToken>
, 1895)
</taxonomicName>
, to name what appeared to him as a number of well-defined biological species in the sense of Mayr (1963), but which he was unable to diagnose by external 'phenotype' (Scheel 1974, p.98). Later he changed his position (Scheel 1990) and used the names 
<taxonomicName id="BE3BE61B8914F601FE66051B4A5902E9" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Aphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bitaeniatum" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">Aphyosemion (Chromaphyosemion) bitaeniatum</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="733B4310E31C00B775442A019D9198AC" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:78C80644-7E92-46C8-8753-3D4BA9CB628B" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Aphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Aphyosemion bivittatum hollyi Myers 1933:184" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bivittatum" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">A. (C.) bivittatum</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4D8AEA3E75987C9CA5F04ACB3358D450" authority="Boulenger, 1903" authorityName="Boulenger" authorityYear="1903" baseAuthorityName="Boulenger" baseAuthorityYear="1903" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Aphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="loennbergii" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">A. (C.) loennbergii (Boulenger, 1903)</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="0565272D8F4E0C507773277FBCE939C2" authority="Ahl, 1924" authorityName="Ahl" authorityYear="1924" baseAuthorityName="Ahl" baseAuthorityYear="1924" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Aphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pappenheimi" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">A. (C.) pappenheimi (Ahl, 1924)</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="33E43735820B5249386ABE03B315AA11" authority="Ahl, 1924" authorityName="Ahl" authorityYear="1924" baseAuthorityName="Ahl" baseAuthorityYear="1924" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Aphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="riggenbachi" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">A. (C.) riggenbachi (Ahl, 1924)</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4B92C5C5843E856CCD7B075EA26F0EAC" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BAADFA87-906B-4550-9030-E7E8CD6DD087" authority="Radda &amp; Wildekamp, 1977" authorityName="Radda &amp; Wildekamp" authorityYear="1977" baseAuthorityName="Radda &amp; Wildekamp" baseAuthorityYear="1977" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Aphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Aphyosemion volcanum Radda &amp; Wildekamp 1977:137" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="volcanum" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">A. (C.) volcanum (Radda &amp; Wildekamp, 1977)</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="2D8D506E6D0B1C58B297AECEB7986C48" authority="Scheel (1990)" authorityName="Scheel" authorityYear="1990" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bitaeniatum">Chromaphyosemion bitaeniatum sensu Scheel (1990)</taxonomicName>
included the currently recognized species 
<taxonomicName id="7998A3F014D702F637A976EF2B5B335A" authority="Huber, 1998a" authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="1998" baseAuthorityName="Huber" baseAuthorityYear="1998" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alpha">C. alpha (Huber, 1998a)</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="323AF264304F535932A1C42163B0207A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bitaeniatum">C. bitaeniatum</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="1841251323E2404D7E65FD97F3D0C620" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:6DD323F2-FE35-4ED3-B8CD-FB129111161F" authority="Legros, 1999" authorityName="Legros" authorityYear="1999" baseAuthorityName="Legros" baseAuthorityYear="1999" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Aphyosemion Chromaphyosemion kouamense Legros 1999:33" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kouamense">C. kouamense (Legros, 1999)</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="746671660BB8CD27491CFDA44B2C3048" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:494F6568-0395-45FD-B6C4-99E11F027244" authority="Legros et al., 2005" authorityName="Legros" authorityYear="2005" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Chromaphyosemion melanogaster Legros, Zentz &amp; Agnèse 2005" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="melanogaster">C. melanogaster Legros et al., 2005</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="CFC55AE3DC21A3F051EA041A3836D9A6" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:FD680552-D332-415D-8B46-60937B2486FC" authority="Amiet, 1991" authorityName="Amiet" authorityYear="1991" baseAuthorityName="Amiet" baseAuthorityYear="1991" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Aphyosemion Chromaphyosemion poliaki Amiet 1991:89" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="poliaki">C. poliaki (Amiet, 1991)</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="96F79AE28A78E0300777607C9951A68F" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:58293C95-476D-42FC-B52D-62A8938702E3" authority="Legros et al., 2005" authorityName="Legros" authorityYear="2005" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Chromaphyosemion punctulatum Legros, Zentz &amp; Agnèse 2005" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="punctulatum">C. punctulatum Legros et al., 2005</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="F743A2767D6563298F0448E46B95A3CF" authority="Bruening, 1929a" authorityName="Bruening" authorityYear="1929" baseAuthorityName="Bruening" baseAuthorityYear="1929" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendopleure">
C. splendopleure (
<normalizedToken id="A2DCAB8FC163F6900119729654696E79" originalValue="Brün-">Bruening</normalizedToken>
, 1929a)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="693B8E4ABEABC2B268C4415402EE69A5" pageNumber="3">
Currently 
<taxonomicName id="D086CF746D64DD0D526EA25506442729" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10DF0F9D-4060-4E5F-A156-DFE88550256D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Chromaphyosemion Aphyosemion Radda 1971:118" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">Chromaphyosemion</taxonomicName>
consists of 12 or 13 accepted species (depending on the author) and several undescribed forms (
<normalizedToken id="1D0C9D4C4534F464F741E804F598A83F" originalValue="Agnèse">Agnese</normalizedToken>
et al. 2006; Huber 2000; Legros et al. 2005; Legros &amp; Zentz 2007; Sonnenberg 2000). Most of the undescribed forms are included in a polymorphic species 
<taxonomicName id="73DDAF6B651A5F3E52233B5F07145B26" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendopleure">Chromaphyosemion splendopleure</taxonomicName>
, an ill-defined assemblage of probably separate species (Eberl 1996; Eigelshofen 1998; Legros et al. 2005; Sonnenberg 2000) or as in 
<normalizedToken id="05683EE9B0A311E0AB4B78177295FAB0" originalValue="Agnèse">Agnese</normalizedToken>
et al. (2006) and Legros and Zentz (2007) in the nominal taxa 
<taxonomicName id="6D3D8BB1DF7040B6675D88623D42B4C9" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendopleure">C. splendopleure</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="B3D2A411BC10B435272A957E4AEF3CEE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="volcanum">C. volcanum</taxonomicName>
. A recent overview of this genus (Sonnenberg 2000) distinguished 16 different forms on the basis of color pattern differences, including nine described species and seven undescribed forms. Two of the latter were recently described as valid species (Legros et al. 2005). Additionally, there are at least two different forms known from mainland Equatorial Guinea, one of them recently described as 
<taxonomicName id="9F6E636F0F34132E84F5A1E7D251AFA0" authority="Legros &amp; Zentz 2007" authorityName="Legros &amp; Zentz" authorityYear="2007" baseAuthorityName="Legros &amp; Zentz" baseAuthorityYear="2007" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="malumbresi">Chromaphyosemion malumbresi (Legros &amp; Zentz 2007)</taxonomicName>
, one from Bioko, formerly Fernando Poo (Huber 2000; Legros &amp; Zentz 2007; Pohlmann 2006a; Roman 1971; Scheel 1974; Thys van den Audenaerde 1967), and recently a probable new species was found in the eastern Niger delta in Nigeria (Alders 2005).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4117DD44F42AA891FC56624691126BBD" lastPageNumber="4" pageNumber="3">
Huber (1998 a, b) postulated an 'artificial' subdivision of 
<taxonomicName id="EAA0A93F93B869AFC9B06A115CAD46DE" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:10DF0F9D-4060-4E5F-A156-DFE88550256D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Chromaphyosemion Aphyosemion Radda 1971:118" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus" subGenus="Chromaphyosemion">Chromaphyosemion</taxonomicName>
into three to four subgroups on color pattern similarities, based on his observations and data from Legros: the 
<taxonomicName id="FAC6C59F824941E5CE3200DFED25C198" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bitaeniatum">C. bitaeniatum</taxonomicName>
subgroup, including 
<taxonomicName id="2C6204BF3E67E8BFC57B3570FE8E20C1" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendopleure">C. splendopleure</taxonomicName>
in the widest sense, 
<taxonomicName id="55AE3ADF8C90C79259C503692667909C" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="volcanum">C. volcanum</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C4A0A113AD5EB385E3A7A0C6F9CDB700" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alpha">C. alpha</taxonomicName>
(based on the absence of red or dark markings on the anal fin, more obvious dark lateral stripes, lines on the snout and a dark postopercular blotch, less and smaller dots on sides); the 
<taxonomicName id="A5562271AB018112E27347FC61825972" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="loennbergii">C. loennbergii</taxonomicName>
subgroup with 
<taxonomicName id="1F9988713B0BB5F77A1C13D338C2FC31" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pappenheimi">C. pappenheimi</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="1874BB7BF199DEA183BAC1F293EF9F39" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="riggenbachi">C. riggenbachi</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C4DC8CAFC2C24C04FD9A711F4C17FE35" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:6DD323F2-FE35-4ED3-B8CD-FB129111161F" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Aphyosemion Chromaphyosemion kouamense Legros 1999:33" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kouamense">C. kouamense</taxonomicName>
(based on anal, caudal and dorsal fins with more or less red streaks or dots, paler dark lateral stripes and in females an anal fin with red dots); and the 
<taxonomicName id="7A6DBDE20F6A3EEBE7E9B032AC46F86E" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bivittatum">C. bivittatum</taxonomicName>
subgroup with 
<taxonomicName id="6B403CC8BA5AC5BDDAEF72C15DAC05A2" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F722B043-3B19-4507-B897-8F3C3146B9B0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Aphyosemion Chromaphyosemion lugens Amiet 1991:85" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lugens">C. lugens</taxonomicName>
, a 'melanophoric' subgroup in which the males have black or dark red blotches on (mainly upper) sides and unpaired fins instead of smaller dots, the dark lateral stripes are conspicuous in both sexes, and the anal fin only in females without dots or streaks. He also tentatively included 
<taxonomicName id="39CAC65902B7D1B1E3DDC078EF9FDCDA" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:FD680552-D332-415D-8B46-60937B2486FC" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Aphyosemion Chromaphyosemion poliaki Amiet 1991:89" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="poliaki">C. poliaki</taxonomicName>
in this group, which he separated on the following characters from the previous groups: red pigmentation around scales and many red dots in fins, males with golden-yellow coloration within the reticulated pattern on sides and a conspicuous postopercular blotch.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="91DF676720C6487D7534342E9868B22C" pageNumber="4">
Recent molecular genetic studies (
<normalizedToken id="33B58F69E20A177577B89FA30BE9B078" originalValue="Agnèse">Agnese</normalizedToken>
et al. 2006; Legros et al. 2005; Legros &amp; Zentz 2007) presented a phylogeny of this genus based on mitochondrial DNA data from the majority of the currently known species and undescribed forms and defined the taxa 
<taxonomicName id="1E10AA76C1AF8D1AC90368FF85179411" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendopleure">C. splendopleure</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="C471777A3A517E26B49D76FA5F458B61" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="volcanum">C. volcanum</taxonomicName>
through genetic clusters, which are at least partially incongruent with current assumptions on species limits based on male color patterns and opinions on the validity of the taxon 
<taxonomicName id="7E618F9F4E0EFB0534B6C0BEDC44C280" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="volcanum">C. volcanum</taxonomicName>
(e.g. Eberl 1996; Eigelshofen 1998; Sonnenberg 2000).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9CD4D3DF81F69AC60769D67BF45E3EB7" pageNumber="4">
Here I present a molecular phylogeny based on a preliminary mtDNA analysis of this genus including all currently described species and most undescribed forms. I used this phylogeny based on molecular data in order to recognize the diagnostic value of (color) characters, especially for closely related species, and review some of the taxonomic conclusions of recent publications (
<normalizedToken id="D292B5DDC9C5A07CE59CF7AE4D14EF06" originalValue="Agnèse">Agnese</normalizedToken>
et al. 2006; Legros et al. 2005; Legros &amp; Zentz 2007). The insufficiently diagnosed taxon 
<taxonomicName id="DCC490DF20FB8018686D8C1FB3C6168D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Nothobranchiidae" genus="Chromaphyosemion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="4" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="splendopleure">C. splendopleure</taxonomicName>
could be restricted to a small set of closely related forms. Three forms from Cameroon that belong to different groups are described, based on diagnostic characters of male color patterns.
</paragraph>
